<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
  <chapter xml:id="ch-subsetting" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Subsetting</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        R's subsetting operators are powerful and fast. Mastery of subsetting
        allows you to succinctly express complex operations in a way that few
        other languages can match. Subsetting is hard to learn because you need
        to master a number of interrelated concepts:
      </p>

      <p><ul>
        <li><p>
          The six types of thing that you can subset with.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          The three subsetting operators: <c>[[</c>, <c>[</c>, and
          <c>$</c>.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          How different objects behave with subsetting.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          The use of subsetting in conjunction with assignment.
        </p></li>
      </ul></p>
    </introduction>

    <section xml:id="sec-subset-atomic">
      <title>Selecting multiple elements</title>

      <p>
        Use <c>[</c> to select any number of elements from a vector. For
        example, <c>x[c(2, 1)]</c> returns the second and first elements of
        vector <c>x</c>. There are six types of thing you can subset a vector
        with:
      </p>

      <p><ul>
        <li><p>
          <em>Positive integers</em> return elements at the specified positions.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          <em>Negative integers</em> exclude elements at the specified positions.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          <em>Logical vectors</em> select elements where the corresponding
          logical value is <c>TRUE</c>.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          <em>Nothing</em> returns the original vector.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          <em>Zero</em> returns a zero-length vector.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          <em>Character vectors</em> return elements with matching names.
        </p></li>
      </ul></p>
    </section>

  </chapter>
